00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:19.760
Andras Visky was born in
Targu-Mures, [Inaudible], Romania.

00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:27.100
He is a poet, playwright, and
essayist, and resident dramaturg

00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:31.680
at Cluj-Napoca Hungarian Theater in
Romania where he holds the position

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:34.510
of Associate Artistic Director.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:37.790
He holds a Doctorate of
Liberal Arts from the University

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:39.640
of Theater and Film in Budapest.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:45.030
And since 1994, his lecture
at the [Inaudible] University

00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:48.670
in [Inaudible] in the Department
of Theater and Television.

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:53.250
He is one of the cofounders and
the former Executive Director

00:01:53.250 --> 00:01:55.820
of [Inaudible] Publishing.

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:57.760
His plays have been
staged in various countries

00:01:57.760 --> 00:01:59.990
of Europe and the United States.

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:03.880
His work will now reach an
English-speaking audience

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:08.810
with his latest book,
"Barrack Dramaturgy," published

00:02:08.810 --> 00:02:13.030
by Intellect Books and distributed
by the University of Chicago Press.

00:02:13.030 --> 00:02:17.050
It contains an anthology of
his well-known plays as well

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:21.020
as a critical analysis of his
theory of considering the theater

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:26.050
as a space for exploring feelings
of cultural and personal captivity.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:30.620 position:56%
This collection makes use of
scripts and director's notes as well

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:34.400
as interviews and creative
teams behind the productions

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:39.580
and reveals an insider's view
of Mr. Visky's artistic vision.

00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:43.480
And we have a small display of
his books outside all of this room

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:47.130
that you can view as you leave.

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:52.510
It is my pleasure to introduce
to you Dr. Andras Visky.

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:59.100
[ Applause ]

00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:00.400
&gt;&gt; Andras Visky: Thank
you very much.

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:02.020
Thanks for coming.

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:08.390
Thank you, Ken, Erica, Natalia.

00:03:08.390 --> 00:03:15.930
I plan today to speak
mostly about this book,

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:23.850
about this "Barrack
Dramaturgy," which was created

00:03:23.850 --> 00:03:28.170
by me many, many years ago.

00:03:28.170 --> 00:03:35.900
So I would like to begin
by telling you that for me,

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:43.520
the theater is a tool
for creating tools.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:49.490
I used to say that the
theater is not a place

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:52.010
for me for entertainment.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:58.270 position:56%
It's a place for serious gatherings.

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:01.630
That doesn't mean that I don't

00:04:01.630 --> 00:04:07.250
like when my audience would
laugh during the show,

00:04:07.250 --> 00:04:14.050
but I think that this
is not the purpose.

00:04:14.050 --> 00:04:22.590
First of all, let's see
how I got to this idea

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:27.020
of considering the theater
a real event for everybody

00:04:27.020 --> 00:04:28.480
who takes part in the show.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:37.240
I never divide the space of the
theater into the space of the show

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:39.690
and the space of the audience.

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:42.060
I think that these two are emerging

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:44.800
to get our penetrating
into each other.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:47.380
My first memory as a child was

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:50.980
when I was one-year-old,
that I'm a prisoner.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:05:00.650
After '56 -- I think that
most of you are familiar

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:05.250
with the Hungarian
revolution in '56.

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:11.740
In Romania more than
30,000 potential opposers

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:14.820
of the regime were
sentenced in prison.

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:18.370
My father was sentenced
for 22 years.

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:23.090
So I don't have even
a personal memory

00:05:23.090 --> 00:05:25.100
of my father before
his imprisonment.

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:29.150
Then we were removed
in a prison camp.

00:05:29.150 --> 00:05:32.190
My mother, an Austrian, grown
up in Budapest, Hungary,

00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:36.810
not knowing one word
in Romanian language,

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:39.440
and we spent more than four years.

00:05:39.440 --> 00:05:44.360
My father served almost
7 years in the prison.

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:46.690
We didn't know about each other.

00:05:46.690 --> 00:05:55.920
We didn't know about him, where
he was, is he alive or not.

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:58.440
We were totally separated.

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:03.930
I am the seventh in my family, so
my mother with seven very active

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:06.970
and very hungry kids, ended
up in this prison camp

00:06:06.970 --> 00:06:09.970
which had become later
on a very famous village

00:06:09.970 --> 00:06:13.500
for the Romanian intelligentsia,

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:17.540
because very interesting
people were sentenced together

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:20.690
with us to live there.

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:22.650
This is the family here.

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:25.120
That man, [Inaudible],
was a student.

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:28.370
He was a student during
the Hungarian revolution.

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:31.130
He was a student in
Timisoara and now he is a page

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:35.140
of the Romanian history
because he was the one

00:06:35.140 --> 00:06:41.560
who formulated the [inaudible] of
the Romanian students influenced

00:06:41.560 --> 00:06:47.030
by the Hungarian revolution
in Romania.

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:53.440
So after prison, he was sentenced
again, not to go home but to stay

00:06:53.440 --> 00:07:05.250
in this prison camp which
is probably familiar to you

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:10.870
because of the novels
of Solzhenitsyn

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:12.490
or Shalam Wolf [phonetic], right?

00:07:12.490 --> 00:07:15.910
So you can see how a
barrack would look.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:18.320
It's behind us.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:23.220
I am down there, the fairly
depressed youngest child.

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:25.930
Here is a famous photo.

00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:28.360 position:56%
It is the winter in our prison camp.

00:07:28.360 --> 00:07:31.930
The printers were unbelievably
strong.

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:36.320
There is a wind which is called
[inaudible] coming from Russia

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.520
and brings a lot of snow.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:43.910 position:56%
For instance, I remember when the
snow covered up totally our barrack,

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:49.710
but it happened very often during
the - It was a plain field,

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:51.190
no trees, only these barracks,

00:07:51.190 --> 00:07:53.990
and we got covered up
totally by the snow.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:58.990
I thought for years that this was
only the image of my imagination.

00:07:58.990 --> 00:08:03.170
And then I found from photography
how the people are working

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:04.470
on their roof.

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:06.960
It's like a Chagall painting.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:12.150
The people floating
above their homes

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:18.150
and being a part of a mythology.

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:24.260
So what am speaking about
now is that, for me,

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:29.700
it's hardly separable -- the
reality from the mythology.

00:08:29.700 --> 00:08:37.520
I think that the imagination--

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:40.860
sometimes it's a much
stronger reality

00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:44.730
than the reality, which
is hiding from us.

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:48.330 position:56%
It's very hard to grasp the reality.

00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:54.720
Actually, this is the main
reason we are doing theater,

00:08:54.720 --> 00:09:04.650
not to create an illusion but to
create a counter reality in order

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:15.180
to understand better
our own reality.

00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:43.840
The man there -- I
really love this picture.

00:10:43.840 --> 00:10:49.870
His name is Paul Goma, a
famous Romanian author who,

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:54.120
after the prison, came to our camp.

00:10:55.280 --> 00:11:05.310 position:56%
Now, this is a map of the camp, done
by that student who is behind us

00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:09.640
in the camp, a very famous map.

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:15.840 position:56%
I have the original one but there
is a version in a museum in Romania,

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:19.990
the Museum of the Communist
Terror in Romania in [Inaudible].

00:11:19.990 --> 00:11:23.880
You can find our name also there.

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:27.410
Let me show it to you.

00:11:35.010 --> 00:11:36.310
[ Laughter ]

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:41.250
This is the family Visky.

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.210
But there are other
very famous names also.

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:53.090
For instance, in the same
village lived the wife

00:11:53.090 --> 00:12:00.570
of the former prime minister
of Romania, Maria Antonescu.

00:12:00.570 --> 00:12:03.590
I remember her very well.

00:12:03.590 --> 00:12:10.230
Former members of government,
and you won't believe probably

00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:15.540
that I don't know how
but I'm researching now,

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:20.290
I'm working on a novel
of the village.

00:12:20.290 --> 00:12:29.290
It lands there a piano
also, in this village.

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:37.130
Probably it's like a part of
this theatricality of the place,

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:47.690
or I was together there with
the first Romanian woman pilot,

00:12:47.690 --> 00:12:55.490
Nadia Russo [phonetic], a
very well-known name now.

00:12:55.490 --> 00:13:01.020
So let's come back to the cover.

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:13.010
So I think that this experience of
being a prisoner first for myself,

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:18.890
than being released
during the dictatorship,

00:13:18.890 --> 00:13:25.310
so it was a semi-freedom
than afterwards, until '89 --

00:13:25.310 --> 00:13:33.780
brought me to this idea that the
captivity is a universal experience

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:35.670
of the humanity.

00:13:35.670 --> 00:13:40.370
I have a definition
of the captivity.

00:13:40.370 --> 00:13:41.950
Now, be attentive.

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:53.850
My definition of captivity is
that captivity is a state of being

00:13:53.850 --> 00:13:58.250
in which we are dislocated
from our bodies.

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:03.090
So we are dislocated
from our bodies.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:04.520
What does it mean?

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:10.600
That the prisoner is
never present in himself.

00:14:10.600 --> 00:14:11.900
He is not there.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:14.630
He is always [inaudible].

00:14:14.630 --> 00:14:19.950
So a prisoner always creates
his or her own double,

00:14:19.950 --> 00:14:26.190
like [Inaudible] would
say, great French artist.

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:33.070
I relate to that double which
is an expression of freedom

00:14:33.070 --> 00:14:36.230
for me but I am a prisoner.

00:14:36.230 --> 00:14:40.870
So what is the theatrical
space for me?

00:14:40.870 --> 00:14:51.660
It's a where we freely shoot
ourselves in order to be set free

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:55.040
by the event, what happens there.

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:57.580
What does it mean to set free?

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:01.230
Don't think about something big.

00:15:01.230 --> 00:15:04.420 position:56%
A special understanding of yourself.

00:15:04.420 --> 00:15:11.280
A new understanding your identity
or your own personal story

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:18.230
or regarding your relationships,
etc. etc. So I think

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:26.940
that the 20th century created
this kind of universal aspect

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:35.010
of the human being to create huge
factories to exterminate people.

00:15:35.010 --> 00:15:39.540
For instance, gulag --
What does it mean, gulag?

00:15:39.540 --> 00:15:45.910
Gulag is an acronym which means
that chief quarter of camps --

00:15:45.910 --> 00:15:50.860
that would be Russian meaning
of this -- corrective camps.

00:15:50.860 --> 00:15:53.150
This is a euphemism
for extermination camp,

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:57.810
because when someone wants to
correct you in a prison, I mean,

00:15:57.810 --> 00:16:00.490
we were political prisoners, right?

00:16:00.490 --> 00:16:03.900
We were there because of our
convictions about freedom,

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:07.000
about the rights of a person.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:11.510
Then a corrective camp means
extermination camp, right?

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:14.970
But at the same time, don't
think that for a child

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:19.960
to be a prisoner in
a gulag camp was sad.

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:21.260
I tried to be happy.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:25.120
My older siblings, they kept
teaching me to recognize my father

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:27.670
on small black and white photos.

00:16:27.670 --> 00:16:34.660 position:56%
And I couldn't recognize him all the
time and that's sort of a big trauma

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:37.550
for me, how to recognize
your father.

00:16:37.550 --> 00:16:40.150
That's not possible.

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:47.430
So my poetry, my writings
are focused on this idea

00:16:47.430 --> 00:16:51.700
of being dislocated and we
are addicted to freedom.

00:16:52.750 --> 00:16:59.570
That would be probably the
definition of a human being.

00:16:59.570 --> 00:17:02.960
So the lack of freedom
creates big traumas for us.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:07.980
If we shut in ourselves
in a theater,

00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:12.050
that means that there
is no hierarchy

00:17:12.050 --> 00:17:15.340
between actors and audience.

00:17:15.340 --> 00:17:18.960
So I don't write stories
for the stage.

00:17:18.960 --> 00:17:24.020
I try to write snapshots with
big open spaces and empty spaces

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:28.450
in order to offer for the
audience to enter in the story,

00:17:28.450 --> 00:17:33.360
to offer for them to recognize
themselves in the play.

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:35.650
So what happens in a cell?

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:38.130 position:56%
The freedom is highly fictionalized.

00:17:38.130 --> 00:17:39.670
The space is always tight.

00:17:39.670 --> 00:17:45.900 position:56%
If you move, you bump into somebody.

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:49.780
If you move, you create a conflict.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:55.770
So the level of the story
within a cell should be much,

00:17:55.770 --> 00:17:59.210
much higher than in normal life.

00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:05.420
And what happens in a cell?

00:18:05.420 --> 00:18:07.380
Obsessive rituals which
you cannot control.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:09.930
You have to follow them.

00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:15.620
These are not happy rituals but
these rituals help you to survive.

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:22.410
So I show to you how
the barrack looked like.

00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:29.450
I remember, for instance, a group
of Franciscan monks who served

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:33.510
in the prison, I don't
know, more than 10 years,

00:18:33.510 --> 00:18:36.900
than they were removed to our camp.

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:45.690
And one of them, he made --
actually, it was a Romanian man --

00:18:45.690 --> 00:18:52.650
he was a priest actually.

00:18:52.650 --> 00:19:08.330
He made a small chapel
in his barrack.

00:20:06.500 --> 00:20:11.590
And I remember going there in
this chapel, entering this chapel

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:26.150
and the lights that dim space and
watching these people like singing

00:20:26.150 --> 00:20:29.440
and elevating their souls.

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:35.470
And I remember very well one
man who was the main singer.

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:43.750
When he came out when the service
ended, he always kissed the ground.

00:20:44.910 --> 00:20:47.730
And that was, for me,
not understandable.

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:51.920
How would you kiss the
ground of your detention?

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:54.970
What is this space about?

00:20:54.970 --> 00:20:58.310
I think that's why I
ended up in the theater,

00:20:58.310 --> 00:21:02.560
because of this theatricality
of the loneliness.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:06.590
And I remember, once
everybody left the barrack

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:10.590
and I stayed there and
I kissed the ground.

00:21:10.590 --> 00:21:15.280
And I feel even today, the
ground, it was very cold.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:17.900
It was not nice at all.

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:20.690
And then again, I couldn't
understand why.

00:21:20.690 --> 00:21:24.000
What's that now?

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.870
So I discovered reality.

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:38.910
I discovered an inner reality which
is as bleak as the outer reality.

00:21:38.910 --> 00:21:43.940
You can disappear in
this inner reality also.

00:21:43.940 --> 00:21:49.510
So I began to write plays.

00:21:49.510 --> 00:21:53.160
That was my main focus, to
follow different situations

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:59.820 position:56%
of imprisonment, dependencies, which
is in the same way an imprisonment.

00:21:59.820 --> 00:22:02.880
So let me show it to you -- images.

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:08.580 position:56%
This is a play which was produced in
Chicago in two different versions,

00:22:08.580 --> 00:22:10.980
and it's called "Juliet."

00:22:10.980 --> 00:22:15.310
It's not called "Romeo and
Juliet," only "Juliet."

00:22:15.310 --> 00:22:22.110
Because in my play,
Romeo is in prison,

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:26.660
and Juliet, my mother, is with us.

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:31.050
So it's a re-writing of Shakespeare
in a way, because my mother went

00:22:31.050 --> 00:22:33.770
to a vast experience in the camp.

00:22:33.770 --> 00:22:39.810
They take her away from us and we
were expecting to remain alone,

00:22:39.810 --> 00:22:44.810
which was one of the most
tragic outcomes for the children

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:48.670
in all kinds of dictatorships,
I think,

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:51.970
because they put you in
different orphanages.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:56.180
So you get cut off from
every personal relationship,

00:22:56.180 --> 00:22:58.040
from everybody.

00:22:58.040 --> 00:22:59.690
And they have taken my mother.

00:22:59.690 --> 00:23:03.450
But after a few days,
she came back to us.

00:23:03.450 --> 00:23:07.700
So I wrote a play about the
disappearance of my mother

00:23:07.700 --> 00:23:11.440
and the resurrection of my mother.

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:17.150
How Juliet is resurrecting in
not the best moment in her grave.

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:25.500
Her name is Julia --
the name of my mother.

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:29.900
So that's why it's
Juliet in the play.

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:36.360
This is another one,
a part of a trilogy.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:42.020
I will speak more about
this a little bit.

00:23:42.020 --> 00:23:44.490
