00:49:19.920 --> 00:49:23.100
I'm not doing it anymore.

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:32.360
I worked on creating out of
the blue a theater department

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:35.890
as a part of our University.

00:49:35.890 --> 00:49:40.210
[Inaudible] University
is a huge university.

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:45.430
We have almost 60,000 students.

00:49:45.430 --> 00:49:53.120
I was very challenged because
of these opportunities,

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:59.940
and then I began to travel
everywhere in the world.

00:49:59.940 --> 00:50:06.970
But I realized that in most of
the big democratic countries,

00:50:06.970 --> 00:50:10.320
everything is almost done.

00:50:10.320 --> 00:50:15.770
I don't want to enter
in something new.

00:50:18.670 --> 00:50:19.560
&gt;&gt; And your writings?

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:21.140
How has it affected your writings?

00:50:21.140 --> 00:50:23.190
&gt;&gt; Andras Visky: Probably a lot.

00:50:23.190 --> 00:50:29.490
I don't know because you don't
have to counter, test for this.

00:50:29.490 --> 00:50:35.710
Just let me tell you one aspect.

00:50:35.710 --> 00:50:43.500
It took a long time to kill the
inner censorship in your mind,

00:50:43.500 --> 00:50:47.260
to don't censor yourself.

00:50:47.260 --> 00:50:53.040
You know, because a censorship,
it's both a political aspect

00:50:53.040 --> 00:50:56.260
but it becomes a part
of your identity.

00:50:56.260 --> 00:51:00.240
So you need to be very
courageous to go against this.

00:51:00.240 --> 00:51:04.230
&gt;&gt; It seems like those who
celebrate freedom are those

00:51:04.230 --> 00:51:05.860
who have been in captivity.

00:51:05.860 --> 00:51:11.910
I sense in your works a
longing to go back to captivity

00:51:11.910 --> 00:51:14.630
because of the treasures
and the wonder and the joy

00:51:14.630 --> 00:51:18.750
of experiencing the freedom
that came afterwards.

00:51:18.750 --> 00:51:20.600
And even in that.

00:51:20.600 --> 00:51:29.060
My big question -- is it possible
to find freedom without captivity?

00:51:29.060 --> 00:51:30.680
&gt;&gt; Andras Visky: I think
that the captivity,

00:51:30.680 --> 00:51:36.600
it's not a simple political term.

00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:42.270
It could be a very personal term.

00:51:42.270 --> 00:51:46.850
But this is common sense, that
the freedom is not a given thing,

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:52.440
but I think that the
captivity is a given thing.

00:51:52.440 --> 00:51:56.510
The structure of -- sorry for that,

00:51:56.510 --> 00:52:04.410
but I'm not very optimistic
regarding the human being

00:52:04.410 --> 00:52:07.140
in general.

00:52:07.140 --> 00:52:13.090
Because I got to see things,
a lot of things around me,

00:52:13.090 --> 00:52:18.890
people dying on the street,
in that prison camp also.

00:52:18.890 --> 00:52:26.250
Mothers and were unbelievable,
especially the winters.

00:52:26.250 --> 00:52:31.460
I still dream is this winter?

00:52:31.460 --> 00:52:38.980
I have the sound of the -- For me,
the snowing is not that romantic.

00:52:38.980 --> 00:52:43.600
I could see my mother, how
she tries to hide herself

00:52:43.600 --> 00:52:48.840
to not be watched, how she cries.

00:52:48.840 --> 00:52:51.230
Now, what's next?

00:52:51.230 --> 00:52:59.930
I think that the captivity
- Well, I don't you now

00:52:59.930 --> 00:53:03.190
to become prisoners today.

00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:04.490
I cannot help you.

00:53:04.490 --> 00:53:09.190
The captivity in many
ways makes you mature.

00:53:09.190 --> 00:53:15.580
I was a child, but I noticed
much, much more than many others.

00:53:15.580 --> 00:53:17.810
But in the same time, you know,

00:53:17.810 --> 00:53:26.620
also for me the captivity is a
special experience of the body

00:53:26.620 --> 00:53:36.410
that sometimes I feel that I
remained in many ways a prisoner,

00:53:36.410 --> 00:53:43.200
not having the trust
sometimes in people around me.

00:53:43.200 --> 00:53:49.240
That level of trust you
need to continue your life.

00:53:49.240 --> 00:53:58.520
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] and does
this dramaturgy apply

00:53:58.520 --> 00:54:00.820
to all of your plays?

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:02.120
&gt;&gt; Andras Visky: I don't know.

00:54:02.120 --> 00:54:04.650
Read the book, because there are,
I don't know how many, seven,

00:54:04.650 --> 00:54:09.270
eight critical essays
about what I'm doing now.

00:54:09.270 --> 00:54:15.730 position:56%
But you know, barrack dramaturgy, I
consider the theater being a prison.

00:54:17.390 --> 00:54:21.380
We entered the prison and
we get out from the prison.

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:24.240
For instance, in one of my plays,

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:31.380
we shot the audience
behind the Iron Curtain.

00:54:31.380 --> 00:54:33.470
And it was very meaningful for them

00:54:33.470 --> 00:54:40.220
because the Iron Curtain is a
metaphor of the Eastern Bloc,

00:54:40.220 --> 00:54:43.900
and the concreteness of the iron.

00:54:43.900 --> 00:54:49.900
People were very disturbed
because of that.

00:54:49.900 --> 00:54:54.230
Historically speaking, you know?

00:54:54.230 --> 00:54:58.610
Because you are a director,
historically speaking,

00:54:58.610 --> 00:55:06.690
you know the black box is the
tomb, is the [inaudible] tomb.

00:55:06.690 --> 00:55:11.950
You remember the main
[inaudible], 8th,

00:55:11.950 --> 00:55:20.230
9th century when the theater
again, after 1000 years of silence.

00:55:20.230 --> 00:55:23.750
We hadn't had theater
for 1000 years.

00:55:23.750 --> 00:55:27.730
When I say this, I'm speaking
of professional theater.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:29.660
You know, after the Greek.

00:55:29.660 --> 00:55:35.860
The historians say that it was
1000 years without theater.

00:55:35.860 --> 00:55:39.370
And then in the 8th, 9th century,

00:55:39.370 --> 00:55:44.280
it emerged from the
Catholic liturgy in the West.

00:55:44.280 --> 00:55:50.340
I'm speaking about
the Western countries.

00:55:50.340 --> 00:55:55.930
So I am telling you this,
that the architecture

00:55:55.930 --> 00:56:01.900
of the back box goes
back to the empty tomb.

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:05.180
So what are the actors doing?

00:56:05.180 --> 00:56:07.910
They entered the empty tomb.

00:56:07.910 --> 00:56:11.740
They are dying as persons.

00:56:11.740 --> 00:56:18.970
We see them as characters and they
are coming out from the empty tomb.

00:56:18.970 --> 00:56:20.270
It's the same.

00:56:20.270 --> 00:56:25.890
I barrack dramaturgy for me,
that's why it is important

00:56:25.890 --> 00:56:28.020
because it's very personal,

00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:32.280
and at the same time historically
speaking you have a foundation

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:34.580
for it.

